Next, we estimate a mass of the ejected envelope. A relation between the $N_{\rm{H,CSM}}$
and a hydrogen mass of the ejected envelope ($M_{\rm{H,e}}$) is derived by
\cite{krautter1996} to be
\begin{equation}
 M_{\rm{H,e}} = \frac{4}{3} \pi v_{\rm{e}}^{2} t^{2} m_{\rm{H}} N_{\rm{H,CSM}}
\end{equation}
% ((4/3)*pi()*((3.0E8)^2)*((9*24*60*60)^2)*(1.4E23)*(1.673E-27))/(1.9891E30)
% ((4/3)*pi()*((3.0E8)^2)*((29*24*60*60)^2)*(9.0E21)*(1.673E-27))/(1.9891E30)

It is converted
to $M_{\rm{WD}}$~$\lesssim$~1.3~$M_{\odot}$ using a relation between a white dwarf
radius and a mass
\[
 \frac{R_{\rm{WD}}}{R_{\odot}}=9.3\times10^{-3}\frac{(M_{\rm{Ch}}-M_{\rm{Ch}}(M_{\rm{WD}}/M_{\rm{Ch}})^{4/3})^{1/
2}}{M_{\odot}(M_{\rm{WD}}/M_{\rm{Ch}})^{1/3}}
\]
derived by \citet{nauenberg1972}, where $M_{\rm{Ch}}$ represents the Chandrasekhar's
limit of $\sim$1.4~$M_{\odot}$.


Rwd[m] = (7.8E6)*(((M/1.4)^(-2/3))-((M/1.4)^(2/3)))^(1/2)
